[normal]THE EFFECT OF ‘THIRD PARTY’ PRESSURE ON POLICE CRIME RECORDING PRACTICE[bold]Synopsis[bold]Background[bold] 
[normal]considerations[bold]1. 
[normal]The 
[normal]vast 
[normal]majority of crimes recorded 
[normal]as 
[normal]Notifiable
[normal] Offences 
[normal]by the 
[normal]police 
[normal]are the result of complaints made to them by members of the public
[normal] (individual and corporate)
[normal], usually because they believe themselves to have been the victims of crime. 
[normal]T
[normal]he belief that the statistics of Recorded Crime are a 
[normal]true 
[normal]measure of the extent of crime that occurs is no longer 
[normal]credible since it is no longer plausible to believe that the police are the only means 
[normal]in society 
[normal]for 
[normal]dealing
[normal] with crime, that they are capable of surveillance and investigation sufficient to detect all wrong-doing, or that the public report all the crime that they encounter. Nevertheless, the media, opinion-leaders and the police service itself often seek to foster this anachronistic view of the police for a variety of reasons. The pursuit of such a fiction leads to public scepticism and mistrust not only of police crime recording but also of the police service as a whole.
[normal]2. Nowadays, recorded crime is 
[normal]best seen as an output measure of the 
[normal]public police services. 
[normal]The fundamental difficulty with Recorded Crime statistics is that they are at once both a measure of the demand for public police service and a measure of the supply of 
[normal]those 
[normal]services in response to that demand. Several issues compound the difficulty:
[normal]Types of third-party pressure on crime recording[bold]2. There are various kinds of third-party pressure on police recording, having different bearings upon complainants and police services respectively. The main types are:
[normal]These various pressures upon the police can have countervailing effects upon the volume and the type of crime that they record, which may vary from place to place and time to time. Some types of crime, some types of community, and different governance regimes, may all be likely to affect police discretionary recording and therefore the volume of crimes recorded. 
[normal]Systematic recording adjustment[bold]3. I
[normal]t is also likely that police operate 
[normal]systematic 
[normal]recording discretion as a kind of 
[normal]management adjustment
[normal] to the pressures of workload and the constraints of the resources at their disposal.  Different circumstances may lead
[normal], respectively, 
[normal]to different 
[normal]and separate 
[normal]pressures on police resources and accountability
[normal]. Reconciling these may lead to systematic adjustments to recording practice.  For instance, w
[normal]hen crime is going up, 
[normal]public and political 
[normal]pressure to reduce crime may increase at the same time as 
[normal]police
[normal] workload is also increasing due to the volume of complaints 
[normal]with which they are obliged to deal.
[normal] Hypothetically, the police may then seek to deflate the volume of recorded crime 
[normal]by systematic under-recording
[normal] 
[normal]in order 
[normal]to reconcile these conflict
[normal]ing pressures
[normal]. By the same token, when crime is dropping, the police may be able to afford to do 
[normal](or be seen to do) 
[normal]more, thus relax
[normal]ing the incentive to 
[normal]under-record
[normal]. Nevertheless, if their resources are also declining (or they are incapable of making commensurate efficiency gains) they may then also seek to deflate the recorded crime rate by under-recording.
[normal]The Dark, Light, and Grey Figures of crime[bold]4. Since the exercise of police discretion in crime recording lies beneath the radar of public accountability, its true nature can only be investigated by means of forensic ‘case tracking’ audit methods, such as those employed by HM Inspectorate of Constabulary. Even so, while these methods look in detail at the circumstantial evidence surrounding individual recording decisions (for example, distinguishing between 
[normal]evidential
[normal] and 
[normal]prima facie
[normal] approaches to recording complaints), they lose something of the ‘bigger picture’ of variation in the 
[normal]volume
[normal] of crime recording, particularly in not being able to pick-up systematic recording effects. To do so requires comparison of trends and patterns in recorded crime against the yardstick of the public’s propensity to 
[normal]report 
[normal]complaints to the police. Disparity between the propensity of the public to report crime and the propensity of the police to record crime can be inferred as the effect of systematic police recording discretion. This can result in three crime rates: 
[normal]Evidence for the ‘grey figure’ (1): Not-[bold]crimeing[bold] and No-[bold]crimeing[bold]? [bold]5. The police services log the calls that come in to their command and control centres from the public, a record of which is modified as a result of the report of the investigating officers, producing an outcome log of incidents attended.  In broad terms, this log can be considered a proxy measure of the demand for police service. Research was undertaken to compare rates of logged incidents resulting from calls from the public with rates of recorded crimes for a large and varied English police service area.
[normal] Overall, there are many more calls to the police than there are crimes recorded from them; less than a fifth (18%) of incidents attended by the police are recorded as 
[normal]Notifiable
[normal] Offences, giving odds of 5 to 1 against a call being recorded as a crime.  It cannot be ascertained from the data whether this under-recording is due to: 
[normal]6. 
[normal]Table 1
[normal] suggests that the most numerous category of incidents to which the public summon the police are incidents of anti-social, disorderly or violent behaviour, although the police seem likely to record only about one-in-five of them as crime. In contrast, although much less numerous, acquisitive incidents comprise the predominant type of incident that the police decide to record as crime. Clearly, there are a variety of reasons for this disparity: while anti-social behaviour may trouble the public most, many incidents may not support or warrant a criminal prosecution; in contrast, since relatively few incidents of property crime result in prosecution, it might be surmised that their higher rate of crime recording has more to do with third-party pressures.
