[normal]7.  Our research also found that the disparity varied between different communities: 
[normal]socially deprived communities 
[normal]not only 
[normal]reported more incidents 
[normal]in total but also had 
[normal]a 
[normal]relatively 
[normal]greater proportion recorded as crimes than better-off communities
[normal]. It is possible that: 
[normal]Whatever the reasons, these findings suggest that the statistics of recorded crime may form an imperfect and misleading measure not only of the problems faced by members of the public but also their actual need for and use of police services. 
[normal]Evidence for the ‘grey figure’ (2): systematic ‘no(t)-[bold]crimeing[bold]’?[bold]8. It may be possible to infer that systematic recording adjustment might be taking place by looking at trends in the disparity between what victims say they report to the police - e.g. to the England and Wales Crime Survey (EWCS) - and what the police record as crime (see ONS, 2013). 
[normal] 
[normal]A 
[normal]comparison 
[normal]can be
[normal] made between 
[normal]an index of the 
[normal]Volume of Reported Crime 
[normal]and 
[normal]a
[normal]n
[normal] 
[normal]index of the 
[normal]Grey Figure 
[normal](i.e. 
[normal]the proportion of crimes reported to the police that appear to have been recorded
[normal]) for two time-periods:
[normal]8. T
[normal]he BCS 
[normal](now EWCS) records separately Burglary-with-
[normal]Loss, and Nil-Loss Burglaries (including attempted burglaries). 
[normal]Although both 
[normal]offences were subject to the same crime
[normal] reduction performance pressure, 
[normal]Burglary
[normal]-with-L
[normal]oss also entails (insurance-required) recording obligations, 
[normal]while attempted and N
[normal]il-Loss Burglaries do not
[normal] (which
[normal] can be seen in the much lower recording rate for the latter
[normal])
[normal]. 
[normal]Figure 1
[normal] 
[normal]suggests
[normal] that when the volume of 
[normal]Burglaries-with-
[normal]Loss went up, the recording rate went down, presumably reflecting a workload adjustment. Happily, w
[normal]hen the volume of reported with-
[normal]loss burglaries declined in the second period and the concomitant workload pressure subsided, the police could afford to let the recording rate rise again (almost to the maximum), thus 
[normal]presumably 
[normal]satisfying their recording obligation 
[normal]to the insurers 
[normal]without prejudicing their performance requirement
[normal] with the Government
[normal]. Conversely, neither 
[normal]insurance 
[normal]obligation nor crime reduction requirement apply to Nil-Loss Burglaries, so that the recording rate remained low and constant across both periods, irrespective of a similar boom-and-bust trend in the volume of this crime
[normal], as shown in 
[normal]Figure 2
[normal]. Furthermore, since the volume of Nil-Loss Burglaries reported had de
[normal]clined less than the volume of With-Loss B
[normal]urglaries, the former now become a proportionately bigger part of the 
[normal]recorded crime figure. contributing to the view that the trend in recorded burglaries might have reflected the effectiveness of household security measures rather than, perhaps, police efforts to manage their workloads. 
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Figure 1: Comparison of Trends in the Volume of Reported Crime and the Percentage of Crime Recorded: 1981-1991 vs. 1991 – 2003/04, Burglary-with-Loss[bold]Figure 2: Comparison of Trends in the Volume of Reported Crime and the Percentage of Crime Recorded: 1981-1991 vs. 1991 – 2003/04, Nil-Loss Burglary[bold]Evidence for the ‘grey figure’ (3): systematic ‘down-[bold]crimeing[bold]’[bold]?
[normal]9. The practice of ‘down-
[normal]crimeing
[normal]’ refers to a situation where a crime is recorded as less serious or more trivial than it might be otherwise. Down-
[normal]crimeing
[normal] may be applied systematically to offences so as to take them out of a framework of performance indicators in order to make the performance appear to look better than it is. The inference that this may have taken place is suggested in 
[normal]Figure 3
[normal], which
[normal] again compares trends in the ‘grey figure’ between the periods 1981-1991 and 1991-2003/04.
[normal] Perhaps reflecting public concern (moral pressure) about the rise in ‘mugging’ during the earlier period, the rate of recording of 
[normal]Robbery 
[normal]had been increasing, although by 1991 this was still less than a half of the robberies that victims said they had reported to the police. However, during the latter period, the reduction of Robbery was designated as one of the Government’s crime reduction targets, which seems to have 
[normal]dampened the enthusiasm of the police to record the offence. That this might be a systematic down-
[normal]crimeing
[normal] adjustment is suggested by the increasing rate of recording of crimes that include some of the elements of the offence of Robbery but were not designated as crime reduction performance targets:
[normal]These trends suggest that through systematic down-
[normal]crimeing
[normal] the police may have been able to continue to respond to moral pressure about violent crime while also evading the performance targets that were also supposed to reflect public concern.
[normal]Summary [bold]10. The analyses presented above demonstrate three 
[normal]decision-
[normal]processes at work in the construction of recorded crime rates:
[normal]The basic decision process is that between the public and the police. Yet the influence of third-party pressure seems to have systemic effects on the police services discretionary practice of crime recording. Since Third Parties  intervene in that decision, by careful adjustment of their policies it might be possible to ‘nudge’ the public and police towards more accurate or reliable
[normal] 
[normal]crime recording. While such alterations of the ‘choice architecture’ of crime recording might seem attractive in principle, this might not be so feasible in practice, since the kinds of third party pressures influencing crime recording also reflect the wide social and political context in which public police services are delivered currently. In the meantime, even the most careful (and costly) auditing of crime recording practice may only serve to keep the worst examples of discretionary recording in check.
